Consider the following program with loop invariants annotated with the respective loop(s):
```
#define assume(e) if(!(e)) return 0;

extern void abort(void);
extern void __assert_fail(const char *, const char *, unsigned int, const char *) __attribute__ ((__nothrow__ , __leaf__)) __attribute__ ((__noreturn__));

int main()
{
	unsigned int x = 0;
	unsigned int y = 10000000;
	unsigned int z=5000000;
	/*@
loop invariant x <= y;
loop invariant z + x >= 5000000;
loop invariant z <= 5000000;
loop invariant (x <= 5000000) ==> (z == 5000000 - (x - 5000000));
loop invariant (x > 5000000) ==> (z == 5000000 - (x - 5000000));
loop invariant 0 <= x <= y;
loop invariant y == 10000000;
loop invariant z + x == 5000000 + (x >= 5000000 ? 5000000 : x);
*/
while(x<y){	
		if(x>=5000000)
			z--;
		x++;
	}
	{;//@ assert(z==0);
}
	return 0;
}
```

The verifier returns the following message.
```
Invariant x <= y on line 12: Partially proven
Invariant z + x >= 5000000 on line 13: Partially proven
Invariant z <= 5000000 on line 14: Partially proven
Invariant x <= 5000000 ==> z == 5000000 - (x - 5000000) on line 15: Unknown
Invariant x > 5000000 ==> z == 5000000 - (x - 5000000) on line 16: Partially proven
Invariant 0 <= x <= y on line 17: Partially proven
Invariant y == 10000000 on line 18: Partially proven
Invariant z + x == 5000000 + (x >= 5000000? 5000000: x) on line 19: Partially proven
Post-condition z == 0 on line 26: Partially proven

```
If an invariant is marked as Unknown, it means that the verifier could not prove it to be inductive.
If an invariant is marked as Partially Proven, it means that the verifier was depending on another assertion/loop invariant to prove its inductiveness.
If an invariant is marked as Valid, it means that the verifier was able to prove it to be inductive.
There could be errors in the loop annotation(s), other than the ones mentioned in the above error message from the verifier.
Please fix all the errors, and provide the corrected loop invariants for the program that is sufficient to verify the post-condition in the program.
Use the ACSL syntax to specify the invariants.

After analyzing the program, the loop invariants can be refined as follows:

```
/*@ 
    loop invariant 0 <= x <= y;
    loop invariant y == 10000000;
    loop invariant x <= 5000000 ==> z == 5000000;
    loop invariant x > 5000000 ==> z == 10000000 - x;
    loop invariant z + x >= 5000000;
    loop invariant z <= 5000000;
*/
```

These loop invariants should be sufficient to verify the post-condition `z == 0`.

